Before we start…

You’ve got some genome assemblies now! Now the fun part begins…

In this tutorial, we are going to run genome assembly quality checks with CheckM, and accurately infer the taxonomy of our genomes by placing them into a genome-wide bacterial phylogeny with the GTDBtk, and finally predict the genes and their functional potential with DRAM.

This tutorial will be a bit different from the previous ones, in that I’ve prepared scripts to install and run the software we need. So the idea is that you finish running these scripts as fast as possible, integrating them at the end so we get enough time to have fun with the results!

Part 3: Run GTDBtk (10min)

A unique initiative to establish standardised microbial taxonomy based on whole genome phylogenies is the Genome Taxonomy Database (GTDB). It uses a similar approach as CheckM: it contains a reference database of 120 single-copy marker proteins from ~65’700 species (317’542 genomes), and a carefully constructed phylogeny. The GTDB taxonomic ranks are standardised by phylogenetic distance. Each time you classify a genome, it searches the 120 marker genes in your genome, aligns it to the reference and places it in the standardised phylogeny. To resolve closely-related genomes at species level and below, it uses an Average Nucleotide Identity (ANI) index.

#  Easy peasy
sbatch ./02_gtdbtk.sh
  • When finished, make sure you have the following files:
/scratch/jgianott/SAGE/SAGE2022_2023/${user}/04_checkm/gtdb/${id}_gtdbtk.bac120.summary.tsv

4: Run DRAM (20min)

Our annotation software will be DRAM, another impressive software that calls genes in your genome, and then annotate the translated proteins using a large array of reference databases (PFAM, KEGG, UniProt, CAZY, MEROPS, and more!). It prides itself on being a data aggreggator, so it can take custom made databases and data from other sources. In this case, we will also feed it with the analysis made by CheckM. One nice thing about DRAM is that it aggregates all data to generate nice overviews of your results that they call the distillate.

  • Run the annotation (DRAM) script
sbatch ./03_dram
  • When finished, make sure you have the following files:
/scratch/jgianott/SAGE/SAGE2022_2023/${user}/05_dram/annoDRAM_${id}/annotations.tsv
/scratch/jgianott/SAGE/SAGE2022_2023/${user}/05_dram/annoDRAM_${id}/distill/
  • When finished:
    • Check for errors in your .err and .out files!
    • Check that the script successfully generated the following:
      • directory ./DRAMkefir/annoDRAM_{genomeID}/
        • with file annotations.tsv inside
      • directory ./DRAMkefir/annoDRAM_{genomeID}/distill
        • with the files genome_stats.tsv and product.html inside

6: Analyse the Results!

GTDBtk Taxonomy

You can check the full taxonomy that GTDBtk resolved for your genome in the 2nd column of the /05_dram/annoDRAM_ESL0976/distill/genome_stats.tsv file. For a deeper inspection of how it came to this result, you can inspect the 04_checkm/gtdb/${id}_gtdbtk.bac120.summary.tsv file. Have a look at that file and decide how trustworthy is this taxonomic assignment. Then fill that part in the google spreadsheet.

CheckM quality

Inspect the CheckM results for your own genome and identify its strong points and its weak points. These are summarised in the genome_stats.tsv file, but you can also explore the checkm output (See the APPENDIX below).

Genes predicted

A good way to give you a quick look at how well the genome is annotated is counting the number of genes/proteins predicted in your genome. They should roughly correspond to 1 gene/protein per 1’000 bp. Can you think of a quick one-liner to count genes? grep -c ‘>’ /scratch/jgianott/SAGE/SAGE2022_2023/\({user}/05_dram/annoDRAM_\){id}/genes.faa

RNAs

All known genomes should have a set of rRNA and some tRNAs. The location of the predicted RNAs in your genome are in files rrnas.tsv and trnas.tsv.

  • Make sure you have at least one copy of the entire rrna operon (5S, 16S, 23S). Are there any discrepancies in copy number?

  • In order to function properly, a cell should in principle have at least one tRNA for each aminoacid. The translation are in the 6th column of the trnas.tsv file. Does your genome has at least one copy for each aminoacid? Does it has different tRNAs for the same aminoacid? awk -F’ ‘{print $6}’ trnas.tsv | sort | uniq -c | wc -l

GC% Distribution

Remember we can identify some radically different contaminations (or viruses, or plasmids) inspecting the GC% skew. CheckM plots this distribution in your 04_checkm/results/plots/gc_plots.png directory. This plot shows the GC% distribution across your genome in fragments of 5,000 bp. How can you use this to evaluate the quality? How would it look like if it contained the mixed genomes of two different bacteria?

Coding Density

Bacteria are constrained in cellular space, and try to keep their genomes as small as possible. Thus bacterial genomes have very high coding density (e.g. there is little non-coding DNA). The plot oin 04_checkm/results/plots/coding_density_plots.png shows the fraction of bases that are inside a coding sequence in moving windows of 1,000 bp. This example has most of them over 80% coding density. Is this a good thing? How would a good/bad assembly look like?

NX values

Remember N50? Well, the plot in 04_checkm/results/plots/nx_plots.png represents a generalization on the N50 (50%) across all percentages wished (N25, N75…), hence Nx. It tells you the length of the shortest contig of the largest contigs (ordered from largest to shortest), when their summed lenght is x, that is 25%, 50%, 75%, etc. Is this plot showing a good assembly? why?

Marker-gene set Analyses

Distribution of the marker-sets

CheckM uses several different genes to estimate completeness. However, many times these conserved genes are in a single operon or in the same chromosomal region (e.g. all ribosomal proteins are usually in the same stretch). This means that losing a relatively short region of DNA could skew the evaluation quite drastically. So the first thing to do is to check how well distributed these genes are across our genome. - The plot in 04_checkm/results/plots/markers_pos_plots.png shows exactly this. Each square is 1 marker set, and the colours indicate how many marker genes it contains. Are they well distributed across your genome or clustered? Why is this important for us? Marker sets are a proxy of what exactly?

Marker-gene sets results

You can find the marker gene results on **Completeness, Contamination* and Strain Heterogeneity either in the CheckM_QC_f2.tsv file or integrated in the genome_stats.tsv file. Inspect these files and decide if those levels of completeness, contamination and strain heterogeneity are sufficient to consider this a good genome assembly. You can read about all CheckM outputs in APPENDIX

Veredict

How do we decide what is a good assembly and what is a bad one? There is no clear cut answer, but there are some common sense guidelines as to what is the minimum needed to report in a newly sequenced genome, and on how its quality shoudl be reported. These are gathered in the Minimum Information about a Genome Sequence specification (MIGS), and its updated form the Minimum Information about a Metagenome-Assembled Genome (MIMAG). Here is a short summary so you get an idea:

  • The output of CheckM is quite extensive and extremely useful to have a full picture of the quality of your genome. You can explore a guide on how to interpret it in the APPENDIX.

When you’ve made a decision, write it in the last column of the group’s spreadsheet (Veredict)(https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/13yoqbjZEOriaUmpEqeuugD-Fp5cr18mVFPInbiTH-sI/edit#gid=1199947108), as Finished/High/Medium/Low quality. Be prepared to defend your decision!!!

APPENDIX - Dissecting CheckM processing and outputs:

CheckM - What is it actually doing?

When invoked, CheckM will do the following:

CheckM flow diagram

  • Calculate the assembly statistics we reviewed last time (size, GC%, N50, etc) on your whole assembly

  • Call (find, deduce, identify) the genes in your genome and translate them

  • Compare these sequences against an internal database of reference genomes containing all Bacteria and Archaea

  • Map the genes from your genome into a tree with all genomes, thus inferring the position of your genome in a reference phylogeny

  • According to its position in the phylogeny, choose a set of marker genes that are single-copy (not duplicated) and conserved (always present) in all members of that clade.

  • Search for this set of marker genes in your genome, and estimate quality.

  • For more information you can read the paper by Parks et al. 2015 that describes it, and peruse the CheckM wiki.

CheckM Output

  • Open the file CheckM_QC_f2.tsv in MSExcel (or your favourite Spreadsheet software). Note that this is formatted with tab-separated-values, you’ll need to tell this to the Spreadsheet. Two things to try:
    • Open it directly in MSExcel and let it ask you about the format. You then choose Character delimited (or whatever is the opposite to Fixed), and select tab as character delimiter, and unselect commas and spaces.
    • Open it in a plain format Text Editor (Notepad, BBEdit, Atom), select everything, copy and paste into a spreadsheet.

This is the key to the columns. Keep in mind that in order to account for gene linkage, CheckM organizes the single-copy marker genes into groups of genes that are typically found close to each other or marker sets, and that these are used to estimate quality:

header Description
Bin_Id Genome ID
Marker lineage Lineage to where your genome was placed in the reference phylogeny, used to infer the marker set
# genomes Number of genomes used to estimate the marker set
# markers Number of marker genes in this marker set
# marker sets Number of groups of co-located marker genes
Completeness Percentage of marker sets found in your query genome
Contamination Percentage of marker sets found more than once in your query genome
Strain heterogeneity Fraction of multicopy marker sets with an Average Aminoacid Identity >90% (closely related strains)
Genome size (bp) Well… genome size
# ambiguous bases Number of bases that are not resolved (N,K,Y,B,?,-)
# scaffolds Number of scaffolds
# contigs Number of contiguous (gap-less) sequences
N50 (scaffolds) Contiguity: length of the shortest scaffold at 50% of the total genome length
N50 (contigs) Contiguity: length of the shortest contig at 50% of the total genome length
Mean scaffold length (bp) Mean scaffold length
Mean contig length (bp) Mean contig length
Longest scaffold (bp) Length of the longest scaffold
Longest contig (bp) Length of the longest contig
GC Percentage of bases that are G or C
GC std (scaffolds > 1kbp) Standard deviation of the GC%
Coding density What fraction of the total genome length belong to a coding sequence
Translation table Codon table used to translate genes into proteins
# predicted genes Number of genes predicted
0 Number of genes from the marker set that are missing from your genome
1 Number of genes from the marker set that were found in single-copy
2 Number of genes from the marker set that were duplicated
3 Number of genes from the marker set that were triplicated
5+ Number of genes from the marker set that were found in 5 or more copies

Marker Lineage

  • This is an indication of the placement of your genome in the reference phylogeny. If it is very close to the tips (species, genus), it means your genome is unambiguously related to one or more genomes in the reference database. If it is far (phylum, class), it means that there are no closely related genomes in the reference database, and the set of marker genes might not be representative for your genome.

Completeness

  • This estimation of completeness tells you how much of what you’d expect to be in your genome was actually found there. The higher the value, the better.

Contamination

  • This is an estimation of the presence of more than two bacterial strains in your assembly. The higher it is, the worst. Finding a few duplications is normal and commonly found in genome sequences. But not when a large part of your marker genes are duplicated.

Strain heterogeneity

  • The presence of multi-copy marker genes might be an indication that your sample was contaminated (for example with a yeast, or human cells), or due to the presence of very closely related, variable strains in the sample. This is not necessarily bad, but it needs to be taken into account and can explain highly fragmented assemblies.
